Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Cost¶

From below descriptions statistics, the mean of cost is around $21859 with median $20180, which suggests a slightly right skewed dataset.

The average cost is much higher than $5407, the average hospital bill in Singapore (reference: TOSP hospital bill benchmark https://www.moh.gov.sg/cost-financing/fee-benchmarks-and-bill-amount-information). Based on TOSP hospital bill benchmarking, bills correspond to the majority of this sample (p25 to p75) are surgeries at private hospitals and unsubsidised public hospitals.

The skewness in accordance with the histogram and medical expenditure in reality. Extremely high medical bills could be due to expense medication, surgeries, intensive care units, etc.

Explore Correlation¶

From below correlation heatmap , it can be observed that symptom 5 exhibits the highest correlation with cost of care, followed by age, medical history 1, medical history 6, symptom 1 to 4, and weight. As BMI is a calculated feature, it is excluded here to avoid influence of confounding variables, although displayed in the heatmap.

Categorical variables are transformed using one-hot encoding. It can be observed that gender male and female has the same absolute correlation value, which implies the cost of care does not differ between female patients and male patients.

In terms of race, Malaysian has relatively higher correlation (0.386) than other races, followed by Indian (0.06). As the majority of Singapore population are Chinese, this factor may be confounding with residence status, which will be further validated. Indeed, foreigners show higher correlation (0.436) than other residence status, followed by permanent residence, which is in accordance with the bill policy in Singapore.

Symptoms¶

  • Patients with symptoms on average have higher cost than those without, especially for symptom 5.
  • For patients with symptom 5, 25% of cost is higher than 75% of those without.

Following patterns can be observed from the table in below section:

  1. For symptom 1 to 4, as the number of symptoms increases, the average cost of care increases. This can be intepreted as when patients are diagnosed with one or more symptoms in the group of symptoms 1 to 4, the more symptoms a patients exhibits, the higher the cost of care tends to be, which could suggest that more symptoms imply higher severity and complexity of a certain type of disease.
  2. The influence of symptoms on the increase of average cost follow the sequence of 4 < 1 < 2 < 3 < 5, which could suggest the severity of disease and complexity of treatment correspond to diagnosis from the symptoms.
  3. Symptom 5 has larger influence on average cost than collective influence of symptoms 2 to 4, but smaller than the collective influence of symptom . This can be observed from the difference between mean cost of patients with only symptom 5 (18665.293012), patients with symptoms 2 to 4 (18441.017145), and patients with symptoms 1 to 4 (20788.698007).

Implication to model design: Introduce an engineered feature to represent sum of occurence for symtom 1 to 4.

Model Exploration¶

Following models are selected for benchmarking performance using cross validation. Since the prediction target is continuous, regression methods are used and score computed as coefficient of determination R^2 of the prediction.

Grid search is used to optimize hyperparameters.

  1. Linear Regression
  2. Decision Tree
  3. Support Vector Machine Regression
  4. Random Forest
  5. Stochastic Gradient Descent Regressor
  6. Keras Neural Network
In [8]:

Linear Regression¶

Linear regression is the simpliest model to start with and despite its simplicity, many times could yield good result.

In [31]:

In [66]:
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
pt = PowerTransformer()

X_trans = scaler.fit_transform(X)
X_trans = pt.fit_transform(X_trans)

y_trans = pt.fit_transform(y.values.reshape(-1,1))

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_trans, y_trans, test_size=0.20, random_state=99)

# R2
lr = LinearRegression()
print('linear regression cv score: {:.3f}'.format(np.mean(cross_val_score(lr, X_trans, y_trans, cv=10))))

# MSE
lr.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = lr.predict(X_test)
y_pred = pt.inverse_transform(y_pred.reshape(-1,1)).flatten().tolist()
y_test = pt.inverse_transform(y_test).flatten().tolist()

mse = mean_squared_error(y_pred, y_test)
print('cv mse: {:.3f}'.format(mse))

linear regression cv score: 0.981
cv mse: 1484305.260

Neural Network¶

Model Design and Evaluation¶

By iteratively adding layers and experimenting with activation functions, the model architecture with the best performance is a 5 layer simple forward feeding neural network.

  • Model 1: baseline model with only 1 input layer and 1 output layer
  • Model 2: added a dense layer with 20 neurons and relu activator; performance improvemnet observed
  • Model 3: added a dense layer with 10 neurons and relu activator; performance improvement observed
  • Model 4: added a dense layer with 10 neurons and sigmoid activator; no performance improvement observed, and therefore rejecting sigmoid activator design
  • Model 5: added a dense layer with 5 neurons and relu activator; performance improvement observed
  • Model 6: added a dense layer with 5 neurons and relu activator; no performance improvement observed, and therefore stop adding more layers
  • Model 7: added a dropout layer with dropout rate 0.1; no performance improvement observed, and therefore rejecting adding dropout layer
  • Model 8: re-evaluate number of neurons in Model 5. Change to 16, 8, 4; converaging speed increased, but no performance improvement observed

Model is evaluated using R2 and mean square error.

In below section, code for model 5 is retained.

# baseline model: Model 1 NT #
##############################

# without transforming y NT: not transformed
scaler = MinMaxScaler()
X_trans = scaler.fit_transform(X)
# separate data into train, test, and validate
X_train, X_validate, y_train, y_validate = train_test_split(X_trans, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=99)
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_train, y_train, test_size=0.20, random_state=99)


def coeff_determination(y_true, y_pred):
    SS_res =  K.sum(K.square( y_true-y_pred )) 
    SS_tot = K.sum(K.square( y_true - K.mean(y_true) ) ) 
    return ( 1 - SS_res/(SS_tot + K.epsilon()) )


def build_model():
    model = Sequential()
    n_input = len(X.columns)
    model.add(Dense(n_input, input_dim=n_input, kernel_initializer='normal', activation='relu'))
    model.add(Dense(1, kernel_initializer='normal')) 
    print(model.summary())
    model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam', metrics=['mse', coeff_determination])
    return model


def train_model(model):
    logdir = os.path.join("logs", datetime.datetime.now().strftime("%Y%m%d-%H%M%S"))
    tensorboard_callback = tf.keras.callbacks.TensorBoard(logdir, histogram_freq=1, profile_batch=0)
    model.fit(x=X_train, y=y_train, 
              batch_size=10, verbose=0,
              epochs=300, validation_data=(X_test, y_test), callbacks=[tensorboard_callback])
    return model
    
trained_model_1 = train_model(build_model())
